<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="116" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,618,1113]" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,542,654,681]" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">Report associated with sponges:</emphasis>
This species was reported as sponge-associated mite in the Laurentian Great Lakes and St. Lawrence River basins, North America (
<bibRefCitation author="Crowell, R. M. &amp; Davids, C." box="[820,1098,691,717]" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" pagination="178 - 186" refId="ref15508" refString="Crowell, R. M. &amp; Davids, C. (1979) Systematics of Unionicola laurentiana, n. sp., and U. nearctica, n. sp., sponge-associated Hydracarina (Parasitengona: Unionicolidae) from North America. The Ohio Journal of Science, 79 (4), 178 - 186." type="journal article" year="1979">Crowell &amp; Davids 1979</bibRefCitation>
). This species was mentioned by 
<bibRefCitation author="Crowell, R. M." box="[235,408,727,753]" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" pagination="265 - 270" refId="ref15456" refString="Crowell, R. M. (1990) Unionicola billieaehonore, new species, a sponge-associated Hydracarina (Acari: Unionicolidae) from New Zealand. New Zealand Journal of Zoology, 17 (2), 265 - 270. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 03014223.1990.10422601" type="journal article" year="1990">Crowell (1990)</bibRefCitation>
as developmentally associated with freshwater sponges in the Northern Hemisphere. This species was also mentioned under possible ‘sponge-mite’ species in North America (
<bibRefCitation author="Vidrine, M. F." box="[1145,1297,763,789]" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" refId="ref20313" refString="Vidrine, M. F. (1996) North American Najadicola and Unionicola: diagnoses and distributions. Gail Q. Vidrine Collectibles, Eunice, Louisiana, 356 pp." type="book" year="1996">Vidrine 1996</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Edwards, D. D. &amp; Vidrine, M. F." pageId="15" pageNumber="116" refId="ref16032" refString="Edwards, D. D. &amp; Vidrine, M. F. (2013) Mites of freshwater mollusks. M. F. Vidrine, Eunice, Louisiana, 336 pp." type="book" year="2013">Edwards &amp; Vidrine 2013</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1437,618,1113]" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,269,835,861]" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">Remarks:</emphasis>
This species belongs to ‘ 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Muller" baseAuthorityYear="1776" box="[550,688,835,860]" class="Arachnida" family="Unionicolidae" genus="Unionicola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassipes">
<emphasis box="[550,688,835,860]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">U. crassipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
—complex’. It needs further study (emphasizing on developmental study) of this mite to get better idea about association with freshwater sponges. 
<bibRefCitation author="Crowell, R. M. &amp; Davids, C." box="[1138,1436,871,897]" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" pagination="178 - 186" refId="ref15508" refString="Crowell, R. M. &amp; Davids, C. (1979) Systematics of Unionicola laurentiana, n. sp., and U. nearctica, n. sp., sponge-associated Hydracarina (Parasitengona: Unionicolidae) from North America. The Ohio Journal of Science, 79 (4), 178 - 186." type="journal article" year="1979">Crowell &amp; Davids (1979)</bibRefCitation>
stated “The distinctiveness of the North American 
<emphasis box="[783,934,907,932]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">U. crassipes-</emphasis>
like mites makes it necessary to re-evaluate the records of those mites. The mites reported by Conroy (1974) were undoubtedly 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crowell &amp; Davids" authorityYear="1979" box="[1146,1286,943,968]" class="Arachnida" family="Unionicolidae" genus="Unionicola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nearctica">
<emphasis box="[1146,1286,943,968]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">U. nearctica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”. [The paper presented by Conroy (1974) in 
<emphasis box="[543,1203,979,1005]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">
IV International congress of Acarologie,Saalfelden, 
<collectingCountry box="[1121,1203,979,1005]" name="Austria" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">Austria</collectingCountry>
</emphasis>
, 1974 was published as Proceedings in 1979 and referred as Conroy, J.C. (1979)]. 
<bibRefCitation author="Crowell, R. M. &amp; Davids, C." box="[886,1174,1015,1041]" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" pagination="178 - 186" refId="ref15508" refString="Crowell, R. M. &amp; Davids, C. (1979) Systematics of Unionicola laurentiana, n. sp., and U. nearctica, n. sp., sponge-associated Hydracarina (Parasitengona: Unionicolidae) from North America. The Ohio Journal of Science, 79 (4), 178 - 186." type="journal article" year="1979">Crowell &amp; Davids (1979)</bibRefCitation>
also commented: “The records of 
<bibRefCitation author="Wolcott, R. H." box="[314,482,1051,1077]" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" pagination="193 - 259" refId="ref21126" refString="Wolcott, R. H. (1899) On the North American species of the genus Atax (Fabr.) Bruz. Transactions of the American Microscopical Society, 20, 193 - 259. https: // doi. org / 10.2307 / 3221258" type="journal article" year="1899">Wolcott (1899)</bibRefCitation>
and materials in the Ruth Marshall Collection appear to be a mixture of 
<taxonomicName box="[1274,1437,1051,1077]" class="Arachnida" family="Unionicolidae" genus="Unionicola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laurentiana">
<emphasis box="[1274,1437,1051,1077]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">U. laurentiana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[245,407,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Crowell &amp; Davids" authorityYear="1979" box="[245,393,1087,1113]" class="Arachnida" family="Unionicolidae" genus="Unionicola" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nearctica">U. nearctica</taxonomicName>
”.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
